│ THOUGHT: The miscompile comes from SLP vectorizer narrowing a 64-bit abs/mul/zext/trunc chain into 32-bit ops and calling llvm.abs.v2i32, which changes semantics because abs is  │
│ applied after 32-bit overflow instead of on the original 64-bit values before trunc. The proper fix is to teach the SLP vectorizer not to sink truncation (or narrow the tree)    │
│ across llvm.abs when the abs is on a wider type than the trunc result. I will inspect SLPVectorizer.cpp for the truncation/narrowing logic and add a guard to bail out when       │
│ encountering abs intrinsics during narrowing, preserving the original i64 chain.                                                                                                  │
│                                                                                                                                                                                   │
│ ```bash                                                                                                                                                                           │
│ ls -la && nl -ba llvm/lib/Transforms/Vectorize/SLPVectorizer.cpp | sed -n '1,220p' && sed -n '220,800p' llvm/lib/Transforms/Vectorize/SLPVectorizer.cpp && grep -n "abs" -nR      │
│ llvm/lib/Transforms/Vectorize && grep -n "canTrunc" -nR llvm/lib/Transforms/Vectorize && grep -n "narrow" -nR llvm/lib/Transforms/Vectorize && sed -n '1,200p'                    │
